llegality and proximity to the state, and their insecurity and permanence. Mumbai's disorderly sidewalks reflect the simmering tensions over livelihood, democracy, and rights that are central to the city but have long been overlooked. In The Slow Boil, these issues are not subsumed into a larger framework, but are explored on their own terms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCivil rightszIndiazMumbai. 0aPublic spacesxPolitical aspectszIndiazMumbai. 0aStreet vendorszIndiazMumbai. 0aStreetsxPolitical aspectszIndiazMumbai. 0aUrban policyzIndiazMumbai. 0aVending standsxPolitical aspectszIndiazMumbai. 4aCitizenship. 4aCorruption. 4aInformality. 4aMumbai. 4aPublic space. 4aRights. 4aStreet vending. 4aStreets. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479939340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804799393423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804799393.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles